<methodology slug="niche-evaluation">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Systematic criteria to evaluate market segment viability: market size (TAM/SAM/SOM), competition positioning, audience accessibility, monetization potential, and personal fit.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>research</tag>
      <tag>niche</tag>
      <tag>evaluation</tag>
      <tag>market-sizing</tag>
      <tag>competition-analysis</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Niche Evaluation</title>

    <summary>After generating ideas, solopreneurs struggle to evaluate which niche is worth pursuing. Niche evaluation is the process of analyzing a market segment to determine if it's viable for your business. A good niche is specific enough to dominate but large enough to sustain revenue.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Choosing based on gut feeling without data leads to picking niches too broad (competing with giants) or too small (no revenue potential). Ignoring competition until it's too late is a common mistake. A systematic scoring framework prevents bias and converts subjective decisions into comparable priority lists.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Choosing among 3-10 candidate niches before committing to a product direction.</item>
        <item>Solopreneur narrowing-down stage: ideas list to top 3 to validate.</item>
        <item>Re-evaluating an existing niche after market signals shift (new entrants, regulation, AI commoditization).</item>
        <item>Pitching investors / stakeholders and needing a defensible scoring rubric.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>After committing — switch to problem-validation, then feature-discovery.</item>
        <item>For very small experiments (one-week tests) where decision overhead exceeds upside.</item>
        <item>When you have only one niche option — score it but don't pretend the comparison is meaningful.</item>
        <item>For commodity markets where the niche is irrelevant (execution speed wins).</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="niche-definition">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Define the niche precisely using this formula: [Product Type] for [Specific Audience] who [Specific Problem].</statement>
        <rationale>Vague definitions prevent effective market research and evaluation. "Project management software" is unsearchable; "task tracking for freelance designers who struggle with client deadlines" is specific enough to research and distinguish from competitors.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Good: "Task tracking for freelance designers who struggle with client deadlines"
Bad: "Project management software"
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="market-size-assessment">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Calculate potential using TAM (Total Addressable Market), SAM (Serviceable Addressable Market), and SOM (Serviceable Obtainable Market). Targets: TAM ≥$1B, SAM ≥$100M, SOM ≥$1M.</statement>
        <rationale>These metrics provide a reality-check on market scale. A niche with TAM &lt;$50M is unlikely to sustain a venture; one with SOM &lt;$1M won't even cover living expenses for a solopreneur.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>TAM: Industry reports, Statista, Gartner, LinkedIn learning data.</item>
        <item>SAM: Your geography/segment slices the TAM.</item>
        <item>SOM: Realistic capture (often 1-5% of SAM in year 3).</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Quick validation using Google Trends (is interest growing?), keyword volume (are people searching?), and community size (are people talking?).</statement>
        <rationale>Declining interest curves and low search volume signal a shrinking niche; community size (Reddit/Discord) indicates demand density and researchability.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="competition-analysis">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Map competitors on a 2x2 matrix: Quality vs. Number of Players. Target position: High quality, few competitors.</statement>
        <rationale>Quadrants reveal strategy: Opportunity Zone (high quality, low competition) is ideal; Premium segment (high quality, many) means proven market but crowded; Race to Bottom (low quality, many) requires speed; Crowded Market (low quality, high quantity) is red flag.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Always map at least 5 competitors.</item>
        <item>If fewer found, flag "low competition signal" with reasoning (emerging category vs. dead market).</item>
        <item>Include non-obvious competitors: DIY solutions (spreadsheets, Notion templates), adjacent tools, "do nothing" option.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="audience-accessibility">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Score audience accessibility 1-5 across: organic reach (Reddit/Twitter/etc), dedicated communities (Discord/Slack), media presence (podcasts/blogs), paid ads availability, and spending power.</statement>
        <rationale>Target average score &gt;3.5. Low accessibility (score &lt;2) means high customer acquisition cost and makes validation interviews hard. If you can't reach the audience affordably, the niche is inefficient regardless of size.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
High accessibility:
- Subreddit with 50k+ members posting daily
- 10+ podcasts covering the niche
- Paid ads available on G2 / industry forums
- Community willing to pay ($50+/month)

Low accessibility:
- Scattered Twitter mentions only
- No aggregated community spaces
- No relevant podcast coverage
- Gatekept professional group (NDA restrictions)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="monetization-potential">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Evaluate revenue models (SaaS, course, templates, consulting, ads) and price points. Question: Can you charge $50+/month or $200+ one-time?</statement>
        <rationale>Willingness to pay is the binding constraint. A large niche that pays $5/month cannot sustain a solopreneur; a small niche paying $500/mo is more viable. Avoid niches where the cost-to-serve &gt; revenue.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>SaaS: $X/mo, recurring.</item>
        <item>Course: $X once, no recurring.</item>
        <item>Templates: $X once, no recurring.</item>
        <item>Consulting: $X/hr, varies.</item>
        <item>Ads: CPM model, yes recurring.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="personal-fit-assessment">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Rate honestly on a 1-5 scale: audience understanding, relevant skills, daily excitement, content-creation ability, network connections. If average &lt;3, reconsider even if market is great.</statement>
        <rationale>Passion matters but won't compensate for bad market. Conversely, a good market with low personal fit means you'll burn out or produce mediocre work. This dimension must come from a self-interview, not auto-scored by agents.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="niche-scoring-formula">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Compute final score: (Market × 0.25) + (Competition × 0.20) + (Accessibility × 0.15) + (Monetization × 0.20) + (Personal Fit × 0.20). Thresholds: &gt;4.0 Excellent, 3.5-4.0 Good, 3.0-3.5 Risky, &lt;3.0 Reconsider.</statement>
        <rationale>The weights reflect priority: market size dominates, personal fit and monetization are co-equal gates, competition and accessibility are supporting factors. These proportions are heuristic, not calibrated; adjust for your risk tolerance.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Niche too broad.</description>
        <reason>Add "for [specific audience]" qualifier; if it matches more than 5% of the internet, it's not a niche.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ignoring competition.</description>
        <reason>Always map at least 5 competitors; "no competition" usually means dead market, not blue ocean.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Overweighting passion.</description>
        <reason>Passion matters but won't compensate for bad market; a bad niche with high personal fit is still a bad niche.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping market size.</description>
        <reason>Even small niches should be quantified; a niche with &lt;$1M SOM can't support a business.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Not talking to audience.</description>
        <reason>Validation requires actual conversations; scoring alone is hypothesis-spinning.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Score each candidate niche through five subagent passes (market, competition, accessibility, monetization, personal fit). Each pass returns JSON with score plus 3 evidence citations. A separate aggregator agent computes the weighted total and ranks niches; the human picks based on ranking plus qualitative gut. Run the comparison sheet side-by-side, never one niche at a time. Personal fit must come from a self-interview, not auto-scored by agents.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Score at least 3 niches in parallel; absolute scores mean little without comparison.</item>
        <item>Lock weights before scoring; tweaking weights to favor a preferred niche is the most common bias.</item>
        <item>Require evidence citations for any score ≥4 — this is the agent's most-fabricated zone.</item>
        <item>Personal fit must come from a self-interview, not an auto-score; LLMs flatter the user.</item>
        <item>Re-score niches every quarter; market entries / regulation can flip the ranking.</item>
        <item>Use Reddit/Discord post frequency as a leading indicator — declining communities = declining niche.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs hallucinate TAM numbers when the niche is narrow (e.g., "AI tools for solo notaries"). Require source URLs or "low confidence".</item>
        <item>"Few competitors" can mean blue ocean OR no demand. Force the agent to distinguish via search-volume plus adjacent-product data.</item>
        <item>Agents over-weight high-quality SaaS competitors and miss spreadsheet/Notion-template alternatives — explicitly include "current workarounds" in the competition prompt.</item>
        <item>Personal fit auto-scoring leaks the user's enthusiasm; surface it as a question, never compute it.</item>
        <item>When asked to compare niches, agents pick the one mentioned first; randomize order.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <list>
        <item>Personal-fit weight (20%) is the most-faked dimension; founders inflate it for ideas they like.</item>
        <item>TAM/SAM/SOM numbers from analyst reports are commonly off by an order of magnitude; treat as ranges.</item>
        <item>Competition matrix becomes static the day you build it; refresh quarterly.</item>
        <item>Accessibility scoring (Reddit/Twitter/podcasts) overrates discoverability for B2B niches where decision-makers don't post publicly.</item>
        <item>A high score doesn't survive contact with one bad interview; this method gates exploration, not decisions.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="worked-examples">
      <example type="good" title="Evaluating AI Writing Tools for Lawyers">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Definition: AI-powered contract drafting tool for solo lawyers who waste hours on repetitive documents.

Scores:
- Market Size: 4 (legal tech $30B+, solo lawyers 350K+ in US)
- Competition: 4 (few specialized tools, mostly generic AI)
- Accessibility: 3 (legal communities exist but gatekept)
- Monetization: 5 (lawyers have money, $200+/mo viable)
- Personal Fit: 3 (knows AI, not law)

Total: 3.85 - Good, but needs domain expertise partner.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Evaluating Habit Tracking for Gamers">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Definition: Gamified habit tracker for PC gamers who want to build healthy routines.

Scores:
- Market Size: 3 (niche within productivity)
- Competition: 3 (habit apps exist, not gaming-focused)
- Accessibility: 5 (Reddit, Twitch, Discord easily reachable)
- Monetization: 2 (gamers resist subscriptions)
- Personal Fit: 5 (is a gamer, understands culture)

Total: 3.4 - Risky due to monetization. Consider one-time purchase model.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="scorecard-template-breakdown">
      <p>The Niche Evaluation Scorecard is filled in five sections. Each section requires specific evidence and a score from 1-5.</p>

      <section name="market-size-section">
        <list>
          <item>Metric: TAM (Total Addressable Market) — industry reports, Statista, Gartner.</item>
          <item>Metric: SAM (Serviceable Addressable Market) — your geography and segment within the TAM.</item>
          <item>Metric: SOM (Serviceable Obtainable Market) — realistic capture in year 3, typically 1-5% of SAM.</item>
          <item>Google Trends: Is interest growing, stable, or declining?</item>
          <item>Keyword Volume: How many monthly searches for "[niche] + [solution]"?</item>
          <item>Community Size: Subreddit members, Discord size, LinkedIn group posts per week — indicators of demand density.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="competition-section">
        <list>
          <item>Competitor list: Name at least 5 direct competitors.</item>
          <item>For each: pricing, positioning, strengths, weaknesses.</item>
          <item>Quadrant placement: mark each as Opportunity (high quality, low competition), Premium (high quality, high competition), Crowded (low quality, high competition), or Race to Bottom (low quality, low competition).</item>
          <item>Include workarounds: spreadsheets, Notion templates, DIY solutions — these are competitors too.</item>
          <item>If you find fewer than 5 competitors, explicitly note whether this signals blue ocean or dead market using search volume and community activity.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="accessibility-section">
        <list>
          <item>Channel: Reddit (subreddit name + member count + post frequency).</item>
          <item>Channel: Twitter/X (hashtag volume, influencer presence).</item>
          <item>Channel: Podcasts (number of shows covering the niche, average listeners).</item>
          <item>Channel: Blogs (number of active blogs, publication frequency).</item>
          <item>Channel: Paid Ads (Google Ads CPM, LinkedIn CPM, industry-specific ad networks).</item>
          <item>Scoring rule: Average all channels; target &gt;3.5. If &lt;2.5, expect high customer-acquisition cost.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="monetization-section">
        <list>
          <item>Model: SaaS (monthly subscription, e.g., $50/mo = $600/yr per customer).</item>
          <item>Model: Course (one-time, e.g., $199 course to 100 students = $19.9k).</item>
          <item>Model: Templates (one-time, e.g., $49 per template to 50 buyers/month = $29.4k/yr).</item>
          <item>Model: Consulting (e.g., $150/hr, 10 hours/week = $78k/yr sustainable).</item>
          <item>Model: Ads (CPM-based, highly variable; calculate using estimated traffic).</item>
          <item>Willingness-to-pay evidence: cite actual price points from similar products, surveys, or interviews.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="personal-fit-section">
        <list>
          <item>Audience understanding: Do you understand their problems deeply? (1-5 scale)</item>
          <item>Relevant skills: Do you have the skills needed to serve them? (1-5)</item>
          <item>Daily excitement: Would you enjoy working on this daily for 2+ years? (1-5)</item>
          <item>Content creation: Can you write, speak, or make content about this niche? (1-5)</item>
          <item>Network connections: Do you know people in this niche who can help? (1-5)</item>
          <item>Scoring rule: Compute the average. Do NOT auto-score this; the founder answers a self-interview.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="final-calculation">
      <p>After filling all five sections with scores, compute the weighted final score:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Niche Score = (Market Size × 0.25) + (Competition × 0.20) +
              (Accessibility × 0.15) + (Monetization × 0.20) +
              (Personal Fit × 0.20)

Thresholds:
- Score > 4.0: Excellent, proceed immediately
- Score 3.5-4.0: Good, validate further
- Score 3.0-3.5: Risky, improve weak areas
- Score < 3.0: Reconsider or pivot
      ]]></code>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/niche-evaluation-scorecard.md" purpose="Complete evaluation scorecard template with all 5 factors, scoring matrix, worked examples, and final decision checklist."/>
    </templates>

